      "prompt": "A flat illustration poster in post-impressionist style. White background with generous white space. All text is left-aligned.\n[LAYOUT — TOP BAR] At the very top, a single line with three items in the same small serif font: \"2026\" flush left, \"POSTER DESIGN\" centered, \"2026\" flush right. Smallest readable font size.\n[LAYOUT — LEFT COLUMN, TOP TO BOTTOM]\n1. Series name in large display serif font, two lines, left-aligned, black: Flora & Reverie\n2. Chinese title in small-weight Song typeface (宋体), slightly smaller: 金鳞戏水 (render correctly as Han characters)\n3. English subtitle in the same fine serif, one size smaller: Goldfish, Golden Scales in Still Water\n[LAYOUT — BOTTOM]\n4. At the very bottom left, a Chinese tagline in tiny Song typeface: 一尾金鳞游，闲散胜浮生\n5. Below it, the smallest font size, a multi-line English paragraph, left-aligned: The goldfish moves as if time were optional. Its fins trail behind like silk left in a current — unhurried, untroubled, ornamental in the oldest sense of the word. To watch one is to practice a kind of forgetting. Whatever you carried in, the water takes.\n[ILLUSTRATION STYLE] The main illustration fills the right half and center, bleeding slightly off the right and top edges. Subject: two goldfish — one large, one small — swimming among trailing aquatic grasses, with a few small rising air bubbles. Painting style: post-impressionist, plein-air watercolor-oil hybrid. Loose, gestural brushstrokes with visible paint texture. Goldfish bodies in luminous amber gold and vermillion orange, translucent fins in thin layered washes — fin edges almost dissolving into the white background. Aquatic grass in loose upward strokes of olive green and pale jade. Background pure white — no water explicitly painted, only implied by plants, bubbles, and the fish's orientation.\n[COMPOSITION] The larger goldfish curves in a gentle arc through the center-right, tail flowing down and left. The smaller goldfish lower, facing the opposite direction — a classic yin-yang pairing. Aquatic grass rises from the bottom edge into the upper third. Three or four small circular bubbles float upward near the larger fish. Generous white space in the upper-left quadrant.\n[COLOR] The goldfish are the sole warm-toned elements — amber-vermillion bodies glow against the white. Everything else cool or neutral: olive grass, blue-gray bubble outlines, faint gray-green shadows beneath the fish for depth. Palette like Song dynasty ceramic glaze — restrained warmth against cool white.\n[OVERALL] The text portion (left side) has a clean white background — no illustration overlaps the text. The whole piece feels like a quiet nature journal elevated to editorial design. Aspect ratio: 3:4 (portrait). No borders or frames.",
