      "prompt": "Generate a single complete image of an [Ultra-Wide Short Drama Scene Storyboard], one full picture, horizontal 3:1 format, no collages, no multi-grids, no divided columns.\nTheme: [scene, e.g. street chase battle / hotel corridor ambush / subway station escape / night market street conflict]\nThe visuals are not an ordinary poster or traditional storyboard panels, but a \"continuous background + multi-time-point character freeze-frames + single-direction plot progression + hand-drawn motion line annotations + bottom timeline\" story-space storyboard.\nThe background must be one complete, continuous, realistic scene that unfolds left to right, without cutting into multiple small frames. The plot advances left to right: left = start, middle = conflict escalation, right = ending focal point.\nThe same protagonist and the same pursuer/opponent appear repeatedly in different positions, representing different time points. Keep character clothing, hairstyle and body type consistent. Each subsequent freeze-frame must be further right than the previous, without going back and forth.\nSuggested rhythm: Enter scene -> Get chased close -> Encounter blockade -> First clash -> Conflict escalation -> Counterattack using surroundings -> Escape to the right.\nIncorporate an exquisite hand-drawn marking system: thin hand-drawn arrows, route labels, small circles, brackets, action focus lines, gaze directions, key-node short tags. Keep text minimal, light, refined — like high-end visual notes, not PPT infographics.\nAdd a lightweight timeline at the bottom, e.g. 00:00 Enter / 00:06 Close chase / 00:12 Blockade / 00:18 Clash / 00:26 Escalation / 00:34 Counterattack / 00:42 Escape.\nOverall: a high-end short-drama scheduling storyboard / action plot planning diagram / continuous scene storyboard / story-space map. Key is clarity: where characters come from, where they head, where conflict escalates, where the ending lands.\nAvoid: collages, multi-grids, comic panels, PPT vibe, top/bottom white borders, text-image splits, character path confusion, back-and-forth reversals, discontinuous spaces, oversized characters, excessive text, crude annotations, low resolution.",
