      "prompt": "Create an ultra-premium minimalist city poster for Paris, reimagined through Chinese artistic aesthetics and ink-wash sensibility. The artwork should feel like a refined contemporary cultural poster where Paris is translated into the visual language of Chinese ink painting, architectural poetry, and extreme negative space. It must feel elegant, airy, intellectual, and collectible, with strong museum-grade poster beauty.\n\nMain composition:\nuse one iconic Paris architectural element as the main visual anchor, such as the Eiffel Tower, a Haussmann balcony, an arched Parisian window, or a wrought-iron bridge detail, but reinterpret it with the compositional grace of a Chinese painting. The element should enter from one side or corner of the frame, similar to an architectural fragment suspended in negative space, rather than showing the entire city literally. The structure should feel sculptural, delicate, and poetic, with realistic material detail but softened through refined ink-wash atmosphere.\n\nChinese artistic transformation:\nfuse Parisian architecture with Chinese artistic language:\n- pale ink washes\n- soft brush-like edges\n- subtle calligraphic line rhythm\n- restrained mineral color accents\n- floating branch, blossom, mist, or drifting petal details\n- carved-seal style typography accents\n- visual breathing room and strong off-white paper emptiness\nThe result should not feel like cliché East-meets-West decoration, but a truly elegant artistic translation of Paris into a Chinese fine-art poster language.\n\nSuggested visual motif:\nfor example, let the upper corner of the Eiffel Tower or an elegant Parisian balcony curve into the frame like a Chinese roof eave composition, with a delicate branch of white blossoms or pale petals extending downward into the empty space. Or use an arched Parisian ironwork form treated with the same compositional restraint as a Chinese garden window. The city should be suggested poetically, not described literally.\n\nColor palette:\noff-white paper, pale ash gray, ink black, muted stone gray, soft charcoal, subtle French blue-gray, tiny restrained accents of cinnabar red seal marks, and possibly a hint of faded gold or pale blossom pink. The palette must stay extremely minimal, quiet, and sophisticated.\n\nBackground:\nmostly clean off-white or rice-paper-like space with subtle texture, almost empty, allowing the architecture and one organic poetic element to breathe. Negative space is critical. No clutter, no busy skyline, no tourist collage.\n\nTypography:\nintegrate highly refined bilingual typography in an artistic editorial way. Include elegant English and Chinese text such as:\n“PARIS”\n“巴黎”\n“CITY OF LIGHT”\n“墨映巴黎”\n“Light in Silence”\nTypography should feel luxurious, understated, and beautifully placed, perhaps in the lower corner or as a vertical seal-style detail. Use a refined serif combined with subtle Chinese calligraphic or seal-script accents. No crude default bold fonts.\n\nMood:\npoetic, minimal, cultured, airy, quiet, timeless, East-meets-West, intellectual, elegant, gallery-worthy.\n\nStyle:\nminimalist city poster, contemporary Chinese ink aesthetics, refined architectural illustration, museum-grade design, negative space mastery, pale watercolor and ink wash, soft realism, premium cultural poster, 8K, collectible, masterpiece.\n\nNegative prompt:\nbusy skyline collage, cartoon Paris, tourist postcard, bright saturated colors, generic Chinese cliché props, crowded composition, ugly typography, crude Chinese font, flat illustration, low resolution, random people, messy background, watermark",
      "prompt_ko": "'용수묵타개세계(수묵으로 세계를 열다)' 시리즈. 파리를 중국 수묵 미학으로 번역한 초미니멀 시티 포스터. 구조 = 랜드마크 전체가 아니라 건축 파편 하나(에펠탑 상단부/오스만 발코니/아치 창)가 중국화 구도처럼 프레임 한쪽에서 진입 + 여백이 주인공(쌀종이 오프화이트) + 흰 꽃가지·꽃잎·안개 등 유기적 시적 요소 1개 + 주사인장(전각) 레드 포인트 + 중영문 이중 타이포(PARIS/巴黎/墨映巴黎). 팔레트 = 먹블랙·애쉬그레이·프렌치 블루그레이·시나바 레드 극소량. 클리셰 동서양 장식이 아닌 진짜 번역이 목표.",
      "gen_prompt": "Create an ultra-premium minimalist city poster for Paris, reimagined through Chinese artistic aesthetics and ink-wash sensibility. The artwork should feel like a refined contemporary cultural poster where Paris is translated into the visual language of Chinese ink painting, architectural poetry, and extreme negative space. It must feel elegant, airy, intellectual, and collectible, with strong museum-grade poster beauty.\n\nMain composition:\nuse one iconic Paris architectural element as the main visual anchor, such as the Eiffel Tower, a Haussmann balcony, an arched Parisian window, or a wrought-iron bridge detail, but reinterpret it with the compositional grace of a Chinese painting. The element should enter from one side or corner of the frame, similar to an architectural fragment suspended in negative space, rather than showing the entire city literally. The structure should feel sculptural, delicate, and poetic, with realistic material detail but softened through refined ink-wash atmosphere.\n\nChinese artistic transformation:\nfuse Parisian architecture with Chinese artistic language:\n- pale ink washes\n- soft brush-like edges\n- subtle calligraphic line rhythm\n- restrained mineral color accents\n- floating branch, blossom, mist, or drifting petal details\n- carved-seal style typography accents\n- visual breathing room and strong off-white paper emptiness\nThe result should not feel like cliché East-meets-West decoration, but a truly elegant artistic translation of Paris into a Chinese fine-art poster language.\n\nSuggested visual motif:\nfor example, let the upper corner of the Eiffel Tower or an elegant Parisian balcony curve into the frame like a Chinese roof eave composition, with a delicate branch of white blossoms or pale petals extending downward into the empty space. Or use an arched Parisian ironwork form treated with the same compositional restraint as a Chinese garden window. The city should be suggested poetically, not described literally.\n\nColor palette:\noff-white paper, pale ash gray, ink black, muted stone gray, soft charcoal, subtle French blue-gray, tiny restrained accents of cinnabar red seal marks, and possibly a hint of faded gold or pale blossom pink. The palette must stay extremely minimal, quiet, and sophisticated.\n\nBackground:\nmostly clean off-white or rice-paper-like space with subtle texture, almost empty, allowing the architecture and one organic poetic element to breathe. Negative space is critical. No clutter, no busy skyline, no tourist collage.\n\nTypography:\nintegrate highly refined bilingual typography in an artistic editorial way. Include elegant English and Chinese text such as:\n“PARIS”\n“巴黎”\n“CITY OF LIGHT”\n“墨映巴黎”\n“Light in Silence”\nTypography should feel luxurious, understated, and beautifully placed, perhaps in the lower corner or as a vertical seal-style detail. Use a refined serif combined with subtle Chinese calligraphic or seal-script accents. No crude default bold fonts.\n\nMood:\npoetic, minimal, cultured, airy, quiet, timeless, East-meets-West, intellectual, elegant, gallery-worthy.\n\nStyle:\nminimalist city poster, contemporary Chinese ink aesthetics, refined architectural illustration, museum-grade design, negative space mastery, pale watercolor and ink wash, soft realism, premium cultural poster, 8K, collectible, masterpiece.\n\nNegative prompt:\nbusy skyline collage, cartoon Paris, tourist postcard, bright saturated colors, generic Chinese cliché props, crowded composition, ugly typography, crude Chinese font, flat illustration, low resolution, random people, messy background, watermark",
