      "prompt": "Create a premium minimalist timeline poster for SIEMENS, themed around “The History of Siemens in Industrial Fields”, designed in the same visual system as a clean central-object infographic campaign poster. The composition should feel like a high-end industrial heritage advertisement: one realistic vertical engineering object in the center, historical milestones branching out on both sides, tiny monochrome technical illustrations, elegant timeline lines, and a strong closing statement at the bottom. The image must feel intelligent, precise, modern, and visually striking, while keeping the layout extremely clean and balanced.\n\nMain composition:\nplace one realistic industrial copper coil or electric motor rotor shaft vertically in the exact center of the poster as the core symbolic object. It should look authentic, engineered, slightly worn but premium, with visible metal texture, fine scratches, copper windings, subtle dust or machine residue, and precise mechanical realism. Tiny particles or metallic filings can scatter delicately around it, suggesting the passage of industrial history. This central object acts as the spine of the timeline and symbolizes Siemens’ role in electrification, automation, and engineering.\n\nTimeline structure:\non both the left and right sides of the central engineering object, create clean, elegant timeline markers with thin lines connecting to small illustrated milestone icons and short captions. The layout must remain airy, minimal, and highly readable, with evenly spaced key dates from Siemens industrial history. Use tiny refined monochrome technical illustrations like miniature engineering sketches or icon-style industrial drawings.\n\nSuggested milestone events:\n- 1847 — Siemens is founded\n- 1866 — The dynamo principle revolutionizes electrical engineering\n- 1879 — Siemens advances electric railway technology\n- 1903 — Expansion into industrial power systems\n- 1950 — Siemens strengthens industrial automation systems\n- 1968 — Industrial control and process engineering expand\n- 1996 — Siemens drives digital factory transformation\n- 2011 — Industry 4.0 and smart manufacturing leadership\n- 2020+ — Intelligent infrastructure, digital twins, and sustainable industrial future\n\nVisual icons:\neach milestone should have a tiny elegant technical illustration beside it, such as:\n- telegraph or early industrial device\n- dynamo machine\n- electric rail system\n- turbine or generator\n- control panel\n- robotic arm\n- factory automation line\n- digital twin / smart industry symbol\nKeep the icon style refined, minimal, and consistent, like a premium industrial museum poster.\n\nColor system:\nthis poster must clearly differ from the Ford version through a SIEMENS-specific color identity:\nSiemens teal, cool cyan-green, steel gray, graphite, brushed aluminum silver, pale ivory background, muted black engineering lines, subtle electric glow accents. Use Siemens teal sparingly but clearly in key graphic points, selected dates, small highlights, or line details. The overall feeling should remain minimal, precise, technological, and premium.\n\nBackground:\nsoft pale off-white or lightly textured industrial paper surface, with subtle engineering-drawing elegance. Keep generous negative space around the central object and timeline. The layout should feel premium, modern, and gallery-worthy.\n\nTypography:\nall text should feel elegant, editorial, and technically sophisticated. Use refined English typography with a clean industrial-modern sensibility. Include a title and bottom statement such as:\n“SIEMENS”\n“THE HISTORY OF INDUSTRIAL PROGRESS”\n“Engineering the Future Since 1847”\nAt the bottom, include a strong concluding line in a premium campaign voice, for example:\n“From electrification to intelligent industry, every era begins with engineering.”\nTypography must be balanced, minimal, and beautifully spaced, never crude or generic.\n\nMood:\nintelligent, modern, technological, historic, engineered, premium, educational, collectible, like a museum poster for industrial innovation.\n\nStyle:\nminimalist infographic poster, premium industrial heritage campaign, elegant timeline layout, realistic central engineering object photography, monochrome technical iconography, clean negative space, Siemens industrial storytelling, ultra-detailed, high-resolution, 8K.\n\nNegative prompt:\nbusy collage, cartoon machinery, overly colorful design, cluttered background, cheap infographic look, generic tech poster, messy text layout, ugly typography, crude bold fonts, low resolution, random props, fake engineering object, unreadable dates, watermark",
